{"cursor":"4766","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name =Jean-Baptiste RichÃ© image =Jean-Baptiste RichÃ©.jpg imagesize =\n| smallimage = caption = order = office =6th President of Haiti term_start\n| =March 1, 1846 term_end =February 27, 1847 primeminister = predecessor =Jean-\n| Louis Pierrot successor =Faustin I of Haiti birth_date =1780 birth_place =Grande-RiviÃ¨re-du-\n| Nord, Saint-Domingue death_date =February 27, 1847 (aged 66 or 67) death_place\n| =Port-au-Prince, Haiti nationality = party = spouse = relations = children\n| =Marie Celile Richie Charles, Estephanie Charles, residence = alma_mater =\n| occupation = profession = Military (divisional general) religion = signature =\n| website = footnotes =\n}}\n\n'Jean-Baptiste RichÃ©' (1780 – February 27, 1847) was a career officer and\ngeneral in the HaÃ¯tian Army. He was made President of HaÃ¯ti on March 1, 1846.\n\nRichÃ© was born free, the son of a prominent free black man of the same name in\nthe North Province of Saint-Domingue (the French colony that later became\nHaÃ¯ti). His father was a sergeant in the colonial militia and probably served in\nthe rebel forces. RichÃ© himself joined the HaÃ¯tian Revolutionaries probably some\ntime in 1801. After HaÃ¯ti gained independence at the end of the revolution in\n1803, RichÃ© joined the forces of Henri Christophe, who in 1807 promoted him to\nthe rank of general and deputy commander of his army. During the civil war that\nfollowed between Alexandre Petion and Christophe, RichÃ© was instrumental in\nChristophe's victory at the Battle of Siebert on January 1, 1807. During the\nsiege of Port-au-Prince in 1811, RichÃ© commanded the left wing of Christophe's\narmy. A loyal officer, RichÃ© quickly became one of Christophe's most trusted\ncommanders, and as a consequence he was placed in command of HaÃ¯ti's Northern\nProvince, where he was effective in subduing the mulatto population.\n\nAfter Christophe's downfall in 1820, RichÃ© supported the new government and was\ntherefore able to retain his post during the subsequent administration of Jean-\nPierre Boyer, and those that followed. This continued until Jean-Louis Pierrot\nbecame President of HaÃ¯ti in 1845. Pierrot attempted to reform the HaÃ¯tian\ngovernment, causing the Boyerist hierarchy of HaÃ¯ti to sponsor a rebellion in\nthe provinces of Port-au-Prince and Artibonite in 1846. The rebel army under\nmulatto control proclaimed RichÃ© president of HaÃ¯ti on March 1, 1846. After much\nof the HaÃ¯tian army sided with the rebels, President Pierrot relinquished his\noffice on March 24, 1846. After gaining the presidency of HaÃ¯ti, one of RichÃ©'s\nfirst acts was to restore the Constitution of 1816.\n\nAs president, RichÃ© was considered a failure by his Boyerist backers. Originally\nintended to be a figurehead, RichÃ© quickly began to take an active role. He soon\nproposed reforms similar to those espoused by former President Pierrot. Probably\nas a result of these proposals he died on February 27, 1847, possibly from being\npoisoned, although this has never been established. RichÃ©'s presidency,\nconsidered ineffective by historians, opened the way for considerable changes in\nthe political landscape of HaÃ¯ti during the succeeding administrations. As a\nresult, his presidency can be considered a turning point in the history of\nHaÃ¯tian politics.\n\nAfter RichÃ©'s death in 1847, he was replaced by Faustin-Ãlie Soulouque, who was\nanticipated to be similar to RichÃ©. Soulouque later appointed himself Emperor\nFaustin I.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n{{Persondata \n| NAME =Riche, Jean Baptiste ALTERNATIVE NAMES = SHORT DESCRIPTION = President\n| of Haiti DATE OF BIRTH = 1780 PLACE OF BIRTH = Grande-RiviÃ¨re-du-Nord, Saint-\n| Domingue DATE OF DEATH =February 28, 1847 PLACE OF DEATH =in office\n}}\n","linknr":195,"url":"Jean-Baptiste_Riché","recorded":1375082099,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Jean-Baptiste_Rich%C3%A9&action=edit","/w/index.php?titl